## Part 3 — MR Approval Rules

This is the most critical part. Set these at the Application subgroup level. They auto-inherit to all repos under it.

### On `develop` branch

| Rule # | Rule name | Approver group | Required count |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Lead approval | `epay-gitlab-vendor-app-lead` | 1 |

Applies to: `feature/* → develop` and `bugfix/* → develop`

---

### On `release/*` branch

| Rule # | Rule name | Approver group | Required count |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Release gate — lead | `epay-gitlab-vendor-app-lead` | 1 |
| 2 | Release gate — architect | `epay-gitlab-vendor-app-maintainer` | 1 |

Both rules must be satisfied independently — GitLab enforces them separately so two leads cannot satisfy rule 2.

Applies to: `develop → release/*` and `bugfix/* → release/*`

---

### On `main` branch

| Rule # | Rule name | Approver group | Required count |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Vendor architect sign-off | `epay-gitlab-vendor-app-maintainer` | 1 |
| 2 | Vendor PM approval — CAB gate | `epay-gitlab-vendor-pm` | 1 |
| 3 | Bank maintainer approval | `epay-gitlab-bank-app-maintainer` | 1 |
| 4 | Bank PM — final gate | `epay-gitlab-bank-app-owner` | 1 |

All 4 rules mandatory. GitLab enforces each independently. Applies to both `release/* → main` and `hotfix/* → main`.

> Rule 2 (Vendor PM) must be approved before Bank rules become relevant — the PM is the CAB gate. GitLab doesn't enforce ordering between rules natively, but the process enforces it: PM approves before raising to Bank.

---

## Part 4 — Additional MR settings (per repo or subgroup)

Set these under GitLab → Settings → Merge Requests:

| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| Merge method | Merge commit |
| Squash commits | Allowed (not required) |
| Pipelines must succeed before merge | Yes |
| All threads must be resolved before merge | Yes |
| Delete source branch on merge | Yes (for `feature/*`, `bugfix/*`, `hotfix/*`) |
| Require MR approvals to be reset when new commits are pushed | Yes |
| Prevent approval by MR author | Yes |
| Prevent approvals by users who add commits | Yes |

---Key implementation notes:

Set everything at the Application subgroup level — all 15 backend repos, 8 frontend repos, SDKs, utilities, simulators inherit automatically. No need to configure per-repo.

The approval rules on `main` use four separate GitLab rules, not one rule with count 4. This matters because GitLab's combined count allows any 4 people from any group to satisfy it — separate rules force each specific group to approve.

For `release/*` — same logic: two separate rules (Lead + Architect) prevent two leads from satisfying the Architect gate.

Push rule branch name regex at subgroup level will block any branch not matching your naming convention on push — devs get an immediate rejection with the regex shown if they try to push `fix-login-bug` instead of `bugfix/EPAY-123-fix-login-bug`.
 



rules:
    - if: '$CI_PIPELINE_SOURCE == "merge_request_event" &&
            $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_SOURCE_BRANCH_NAME =~ /^feature\/.*$/ &&
            $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_TARGET_BRANCH_NAME == "develop"'
      when: on_success
